So probability of survival is 0.75 and probability of remaining a juvinile is 0.67 so our probability of stasis assuming these are independent is 0.75*0.67\approx 0.5.

So probability of survival is 0.75 and probability of maturing is 0.33 so our probability of maturation assuming these are independent is 0.75*0.67\approx 0.25.

ui.markdown("""
    A population is a group of organisms, like people or bears, that live in the same area and interbreed. Population dynamics is the study of how a population changes over time, including the numbers and ages of the organisms in the population.

    Try adjusting the values in the sidebar to see how this changes the ratio of bear cubs, juveniles, and adult bears, as well as the growth or decay of the population over time. Scroll to the bottom to see the linear algebra behind these graphics!
""")


with ui.layout_columns(fill=False):
    
    with ui.value_box():
        ui.markdown(
            """
            Population distribution
            """
        )


        # long term predicted population dist.
        @render.express
        def peigvec():
            eigvec = np.round(pevec()/np.sum(pevec()), decimals=2)
            streigvec = str(list(eigvec))
            ui.markdown(
            "**v**_1 = " + streigvec + "^T")

        @render.plot
        def pie():
            labels = ["Cubs", "Juveniles", "Adults"]
            sizes = pevec()
            ax = plt.gca()

            # plt.title("Long term population distribution")
            plt.title("Utah Black Bear Demographics")
            bearpieplot(ax, sizes, labels)

            # ax.show()
            
            # ax.pie(sizes, labels=labels)
            # ax.pie(sizes, labels=labels)

        ui.markdown(
            """
            The **principal eigenvector** of the transition matrix represents the age distribution the population will approach over time. The age distribution of the population should naturally approach this ratio as time goes on.
            """
        )

    with ui.value_box():
        ui.markdown(
            """
            Population growth
            """
        )

        # long term predicted population growth
        @render.express
        def peigval():
            "λ_1 = " + str(np.round(peval(), decimals=2))

        @render.plot
        def pred():
            x, y = prediction()
            # convert x value to current years
            from datetime import date 
            year_ = date.today().year 
            plt.plot(x+year_, y, 'go-')
            plt.ylim(bottom=0, top=max(3000, y[4]))
            plt.ylabel("Predicted population size")
            plt.xlabel("year")
            plt.title("Utah Black Bear Count")
            ax = plt.gca()
            # ax.title("Long term population growth")

        ui.markdown(
            """
            The **principal eigenvalue** of the transition matrix represents the maximum growth rate of the population. When the age breakdown doesn't match the principal eigenvector, the overall growth rate may be inconsistent, or lower than the predicted rate.
            """
        )

ui.markdown(
    """
    Populations can be modeled using linear algebra. Here we are considering a population of bears. Since bear cubs, juvenile bears, and adult bears all behave differently, we are modeling them as separate categories of bears.
    - Transition matrix
    - Principal eigenvector
    - Perron-Frobenius theorem

    Inspired by work from Brenden Orocu, Dr. Mark Belk, and others, on modeling black bear populations in eastern Utah: https://byu.app.box.com/s/typ96vcpp010vyytqkufpd1qptcnldh3

    Images and demographic information for the default parameter estimates came from the following sources:

    “American Black Bear.” 2024. In Wikipedia. https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=American_black_bear&oldid=1227551752.

    Animals are Awesome, dir. 2017. Baby Black Bear Cubs Playing Compilation. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-2cj5pPe778.

    “Black Bear | Size, Weight, Habitat, Diet, & Facts | Britannica.” n.d. Accessed June 10, 2024. https://www.britannica.com/animal/black-bear.

    “Facts about Florida Black Bears: Life Expectancy.” n.d.-a. Florida Fish And Wildlife Conservation Commission. Accessed June 10, 2024. https://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/wildlife/bear/facts/life-expectancy/.

    “———.” n.d.-b. Florida Fish And Wildlife Conservation Commission. Accessed June 10, 2024. https://myfwc.com/wildlifehabitats/wildlife/bear/facts/life-expectancy/.

    KUTV, Sara Knox. 2021. “Utah’s Drought May Lead to More Aggressive Black Bears.” KUTV. May 18, 2021. https://kutv.com/news/local/utahs-drought-may-lead-to-more-aggressive-black-bears.

    Schnee (KUTV), Brian. 2024. “Biologists Checking on Utah’s Healthy Bear Population, Visiting Dens across the State.” KUTV. March 19, 2024. https://kutv.com/news/local/utah-biologists-checking-on-bear-dens-across-the-state-dwr-wildlife.

    """
)

# # render an image standalone
# @render.image
# def image():
#     from pathlib import Path
#     dir = Path(__file__).resolve().parent

#     return img


# --------------------------------------------------------
# Reactive calculations and effects
# --------------------------------------------------------

# linear algebra
@reactive.calc
def transition_matrix():
    return np.array([
        [0, 0, input.f3()],
        [input.sm1(), input.ss2(), 0],
        [0, input.sm2(), input.ss3()]
    ])/100

@reactive.calc
def eigs():
    return np.linalg.eig(transition_matrix())

@reactive.calc
def prineigs():
    # print(eigs())
    evals = eigs()[0]
    evecs = eigs()[1]
    i = np.argmax(evals)
    return (np.abs(evals[i]), np.abs(evecs[:,i]))

@reactive.calc
def peval():
    return prineigs()[0]

@reactive.calc
def pevec():
    return prineigs()[1]

# plotting population
@reactive.calc
def prediction(init_pop = 2000):
    # about 2000 black bears in Utah in 2024:
    # https://kutv.com/news/local/utah-biologists-checking-on-bear-dens-across-the-state-dwr-wildlife
    years = 5
    x = np.array(range(years))
    # make array full of peval() entries to raise to the power later
    pevalarr = peval()+np.zeros(years)
    return (x, init_pop*np.power(pevalarr, x))

from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.patches import PathPatch
from matplotlib.offsetbox import OffsetImage, AnnotationBbox
import numpy as np

# adopted from
# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/44528024/insert-image-into-pie-chart-slice
def bearpieplot(ax = None, total=None, labels = ["Cubs", "Juveniles", "Adults"]):
    # total = [5,7,4]
    # plt.title('Bears')
    # plt.gca().axis("equal")
    ax.axis("equal")
    ax.pie(total, startangle=90)
    wedges, texts = ax.pie(total, startangle=90, labels=labels,
                            wedgeprops = { 'linewidth': 1, "edgecolor" :"k","fill":False,  })

    def img_to_pie( fn, wedge, xy, zoom=1, subax = None):
        if subax==None: subax=plt.gca()
        im = plt.imread(fn, format='jpg')
        path = wedge.get_path()
        patch = PathPatch(path, facecolor='none')
        subax.add_patch(patch)
        imagebox = OffsetImage(im, zoom=zoom, clip_path=patch, zorder=-10)
        ab = AnnotationBbox(imagebox, xy, xycoords='data', pad=0, frameon=False)
        subax.add_artist(ab)

    # positions = [(-1,0.3),(0,-0.5),(0.5,0.5)]
    # get the center of each pie wedge in radians
    centroids = np.pi/2 + 2 * np.pi * np.array([(sum(total[:i]) + total[i]/2)/sum(total) for i, tot in enumerate(total)])
    # print(centroids)
    # get the x, y
    positions = np.stack([np.cos(centroids), np.sin(centroids)]).T/2
    # positions = np.array([
    #     [-1, 0.3],
    #     [0, -0.5],
    #     [0.5, 0.5]
    # ])
    # print(positions)

    zooms = [0.4,0.4,0.4]

    for i in range(3):
        fn = "images/{}.jpg".format(labels[i])
        img_to_pie(fn, wedges[i], xy=positions[i], zoom=zooms[i] )
        wedges[i].set_zorder(10)

    # plt.show()

    return ax
